WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.720
[Amit Varma]: What is a life well lived? In my darker moments, I could argue that there can be no such thing

00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:14.400
[Amit Varma]: because all lives end in death and then nothing before has any meaning. No, but seriously,

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:19.160
[Amit Varma]: how does one define a life that is worth living, that one can look back on with satisfaction?

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:23.840
[Amit Varma]: When I was young, my notion of a good life had everything to do with goals. I wanted

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:28.840
[Amit Varma]: to achieve ABC, then XYZ, and I thought that would make my life a good one. With age, I've

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:32.200
[Amit Varma]: learned that the joy is in the journey, no matter what the destination is or whether

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:36.680
[Amit Varma]: you even get there. I want to wake up every morning looking forward to the day and having

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:41.200
[Amit Varma]: goals gets in the way of that. We remain stressed about the goals we have yet to achieve. I'd

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:47.060
[Amit Varma]: rather just enjoy the things I do, take pleasure in small joys. Now, many people will also

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:51.440
[Amit Varma]: define a life well lived by speaking about what one has done to make the world a better

00:00:51.440 --> 00:00:56.920
[Amit Varma]: place. This is nebulous and hard to quantify. Anyone who has worked at any job or has bought

00:00:56.920 --> 00:01:02.320
[Amit Varma]: things or sold things has made others better off because all voluntary transactions are

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:06.560
[Amit Varma]: a win-win game. In fact, I'd argue that just by surviving, you make the world a better

00:01:06.560 --> 00:01:11.640
[Amit Varma]: place unless you're always on Twitter. Now, a part of me is sceptical about the rest of

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:16.600
[Amit Varma]: the world. I've quoted that famous line from Kashi Ka Assi before, Bhaar Mein Jai Duniya,

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:21.400
[Amit Varma]: Hum Bajai Harmonia. I want to play my harmonia. And the question then is, how can I make sure

00:01:21.400 --> 00:01:26.420
[Amit Varma]: that I get the most satisfaction from my life? And here, I'm struck by something that my

00:01:26.420 --> 00:01:32.240
[Amit Varma]: guest in this episode says in the second half of our conversation, that her idea of happiness

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:37.640
[Amit Varma]: is to have something to do to keep the mind concentrated. I love that thought. Do something

00:01:37.640 --> 00:01:46.240
[Amit Varma]: you want to do and stay busy doing it. The happiness is in the doing.

